SIMPLE: party
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Party
<hw>Par"ty</hw> <pr>(p⟦aum⟧r"t⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Parties</plw> <pr>(p⟦aum⟧r"t⟦icr⟧z)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[F. <ets>parti</ets> and <ets>partie</ets>, fr. F.
<ets>partir</ets> to part, divide, L. <ets>partire</ets>,
<ets>partiri</ets>. See <er>Part</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A part or portion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The most
<xex>party</xex> of the time.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A number of persons united in opinion or action, as
distinguished from, or opposed to, the rest of a community or
association; esp., one of the parts into which a people is divided on
questions of public policy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Win the noble Brutus to our <qex>party</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The peace both <qex>parties</qex> want is like to last.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A part of a larger body of company; a
detachment;</def> <specif>especially</specif> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <def>a
small body of troops dispatched on special service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A number of persons invited to a social
entertainment; a select company; <as>as, a dinner <ex>party</ex></as>;
also, the entertainment itself; <as>as, to give a
<ex>party</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>One concerned or interested in an affair; one who
takes part with others; a participator; <as>as, he was a <ex>party</ex>
to the plot; a <ex>party</ex> to the contract.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>The plaintiff or the defendant in a lawsuit, whether
an individual, a firm, or corporation; a litigant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cause of both <qex>parties</qex> shall come before the
judges.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Hence, any certain person who is regarded as being
opposed or antagonistic to another.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the jury found that the <qex>party</qex> slain was of English
race, it had been adjudged felony.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Cause; side; interest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have you nothing said⟦br⟧
Upon this <qex>Party</qex> 'gainst the Duke of Albany?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A person; <as>as, he is a queer
<ex>party</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Now accounted a vulgarism.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦ldquo⟧For several generations, our ancestors largely employed
<xex>party</xex> for <xex>person</xex>; but this use of the word, when
it appeared to be reviving, happened to strike, more particularly, the
fancy of the vulgar; and the consequence has been, that the polite have
chosen to leave it in their undisputed possession.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Fitzed.
Hall.</au></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Party jury</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a jury
composed of different parties, as one which is half natives and half
foreigners.</cd> -- <col><b>Party man</b></col>, <cd>a partisan.</cd>
<au>Swift.</au> -- <col><b>Party spirit</b></col>, <cd>a factious and
unreasonable temper, not uncommonly shown by party men.</cd>
<au>Whately.</au> -- <col><b>Party verdict</b></col>, <cd>a joint
verdict.</cd> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Party wall</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <cd>A wall built upon the dividing line
between two adjoining properties, usually having half its thickness on
each property</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>A wall that
separates adjoining houses, as in a block or row.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Party</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Party
<hw>Par"ty</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>parti</ets> divided, fr.
<ets>partir</ets> to divide. See <er>Part</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Partite</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>Parted or
divided, as in the direction or form of one of the ordinaries; <as>as,
an escutcheon <ex>party</ex> per pale</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Partial; favoring one party; partisan.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will be true judge, and not <qex>party</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Charter party</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Charter</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Party</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Party
<hw>Par"ty</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Partly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Party-coated</ent>⟦br⟧
